| L10-A: Scenario test: "Kirby iterated learning produces compositional lexicons" — start with 2 civs sharing a 100-morpheme lexicon; run for 20 generations with `bottleneck_fraction = 0.4`; assert `compositionality_index` rises above 0.3 (the canonical Kirby 1999 result) | `crates/engine/src/language.rs` integration test | L1-C | Charter AC: compositionality emerges from the bottleneck, not from authoring |
| L10-B: Scenario test: "grammar induction produces closed-class morphemes" — run a 50-generation scenario; assert `closed_class_share` stabilizes in `[0.1, 0.3]` (the real-language band per Pagel et al. 2007) | same | L2-B | Charter AC: grammar emerges from frequency, not from an authored rule set |
| L10-C: Scenario test: "writing systems vary by substrate" — start 3 civs with the same `LanguageState` but different `WritingSystemSubstrate` (Logographic / Syllabic / Alphabetic); after 10 generations, assert the 3 `ScriptSignature`s are distinct | same | L3-C | Charter AC: scripts are derived, not authored |
| L10-D: Scenario test: "physics coupling shifts phonology" — start 2 civs with the same `LanguageState`; one at `T_centroid = 0.0` (cold), one at `T_centroid = 1.0` (hot); after 20 generations, assert the hot civ's phoneme distribution has shifted measurably from the cold civ's (the `phonotactic_T_bias` from §2.1) | same | L5-C | Charter AC: language responds to climate |
| L10-E: Scenario test: "social coupling shifts transmission" — start 2 civs with the same `LanguageState`; one with `k_parents = 1` (single-parent transmission), one with `k_parents = 8` (diverse input); after 20 generations, assert the single-parent civ's lexicon is measurably more idiosyncratic (higher `induced_phoneme_entropy` is fine, but the *phoneme distribution* should differ from the diverse-input civ) | same | L1-C, L5-C | Charter AC: language responds to social structure |
| L10-F: Scenario test: "English default + native toggle does not mutate state" — start a civ, set the session `ViewMode = Native`, run the sim for 4096 ticks, then set `ViewMode = English`; assert the `LanguageState.vocabulary` is *bit-identical* before and after the toggle (proves the toggle is render-only) | same + `crates/server/` integration test | L7-C | Charter AC: render toggles never mutate sim state |
| L10-G: Scenario test: "criticality edge of chaos" — run a 4096-tick scenario with default `LanguageEmergenceParams`; assert `lexicon_size_mean` is in `[10, 1000]`, `compositionality_index` is in `[0.3, 0.7]`, `bigram_entropy` is in `[2.0, 4.0]` (the §2.4 target bands) | same | All phases complete | Performance-gated; runs in CI as a regression |
| L10-H: Scenario test: "criticality knob reachability" — for each knob in §4, set it to its heat-death and explosion extremes; assert the system reaches the corresponding failure mode within 1024 ticks (`compositionality_index = 0` for heat-death, `bigram_entropy = log2(|V|)` for explosion); assert setting it back to default returns the system to the target band within 2048 ticks | same | L10-G | Ensures the knobs are *real* knobs, not constants |

### DAG summary (critical path)

```
L0-* (all parallel) → L1-A..E → L2-A..D (depends on L1-A)
                                  ↓
                                L3-A..E (depends on L1-A, L2-A)
                                  ↓
                                L4-A..C (depends on L1-D)        ┐
                                  ↓                                │ can run in parallel
                                L5-A..E (depends on L1-C, L2-B, L3-D)│
                                  ↓                                │
                                L6-A..F (depends on L1-C, L2-B, L5-C)│
                                  ↓                                │
                                L7-A..E (depends on L3-C)        ┘
                                  ↓
                                L8-A..D (depends on L1-C, L2-B, L3-C, L6-D)
                                  ↓
                                L9-A..C (depends on Phase L5 + L6 + L7 + L8 complete)
                                  ↓
                                L10-A..H (depends on Phase L9 complete)
```

**Critical path to acceptance:** L0 → L1 → L2 → L3 → L5 → L6 → L8 → L9 → L10. L4, L7 can run in parallel with the main path.

---

## 7. Test strategy summary

- **Unit tests** (property-based via `proptest`): each new pure function in `language.rs` (L1-B/C/D, L2-B/C, L3-B/C/D) and `social.rs` (L4-B) has invariant tests — same input → same output, distance bounds respected, classifications are non-empty for non-degenerate input, drift is bounded.
- **Integration tests** (hecs World with seeded RNG): the L10-A..H scenarios run for 50–4096 ticks and assert statistical properties of the macro language (compositionality bands, grammar bands, script distinctness, physics-coupling shifts, social-coupling shifts). These are charter-aligned: statistical properties, not bit-identical outcomes.
- **Emergence regression**: `cargo test -p civ-engine -- language_emergence_regression` runs the L10-G 4096-tick scenario and asserts `lexicon_size_mean ∈ [10, 1000]`, `compositionality_index ∈ [0.3, 0.7]`, `bigram_entropy ∈ [2.0, 4.0]`. This runs in CI as a performance-gated test, mirroring the lifecycle regression test in `civ-needs`, the markets regression test in `civ-economy`, and the culture regression test in `civ-agents` (per `civ-culture-emergent.md` P6-G).
- **No determinism requirement** (per charter): tests assert statistical properties of the macro language (compositionality bands, grammar bands, MI bands), not bit-identical outcomes of the per-tick phoneme features. The *function-purity* of the §1.2 induction + §1.5 grammar + §1.6 projection is asserted separately (same inputs → same outputs) so the dashboard / snapshot tests can rely on it.
- **Existing test preservation**: the existing tests in `crates/engine/src/language.rs:235-334` (`tick_language_advances_time_and_drifts_features`, `tick_language_merges_near_identical_phonemes`, `should_split_when_average_distance_exceeds_threshold`, `borrow_word_clones_source_morpheme_for_meaning`) and the existing tests in `crates/agents/src/culture.rs:168-249` (`mutation_moves_traits_but_keeps_bounds`, `isolated_populations_diverge_over_time`, `contact_diffuses_culture_and_creolizes_language`, `kinship_resists_external_contact`) must all continue to pass — the substrate is unchanged, only the iterated-learning bridge + grammar induction + writing-system projection + substrate coupling are added.

---

## 8. What this spec does NOT include

- Any `enum Dialect`, `enum Script`, `enum GrammarType`, `enum WritingSystemKind` *stored* on a cluster, agent, or polity. The only authored enum in the language pipeline is `WritingSubstrateKind` on the *starting* civ preset (§1.6 / L3-A) — a *carried* initial condition, not a live property of the world's state. All other macro labels are pure read-out functions.
- Any `set_language(family)`, `set_script(kind)`, `set_grammar(type)`, or `set_writing_system(id)` callable that mutates the live language state. The substrate is mutated only through `tick_language` + `tick_language_with_induction` + `borrow_word` + `borrow_with_log` (per L9-C invariant test).
- Any direct `civ-lang` → `civ-agents` or `civ-lang` → `civ-diplomacy` API edge. All coupling is the shared substrate gradient (per §2.1 + §2.2), the `sim.snapshot` read-out, and the watch-bus event emission.
- Any re-implementation of `tick_language`, `should_split`, `borrow_word`, `cultural_distance`, `language_distance`, or `drift_populations`. The substrate is correct as of this spec's date; the new work is the iterated-learning bridge + grammar induction + writing-system projection + substrate coupling + the read-out layer.
- Any handcrafted phonotactic table, lexeme list, grammar rule set, or glyph atlas. All of these are derived projections through data tables (per `civ-culture-emergent.md` §1.3 + §2.4 and the Lexifer / Rosenfelder / Zompist LCK references in `emergent-systems-spec.md` §2.4).
- Any LLM call in the language engine path. The cultural register of the legends engine may use the existing LLM garnish for narrative embellishment (per `emergent-systems-spec.md` §2.6 / §2.10 / §11), but the iterated-learning + grammar induction + writing-system projection are pure functions over the substrate.
- Any music / audio *generation* component. This spec extends `MusicalTradition` to read the new `bigram_entropy` input (per L8-C / §5.8), but the actual audio synthesis is the domain of [`audio-direction.md`](audio-direction.md) + `emergent-systems-spec.md` §2.5 (E6).
- Any change to the English default. English is the player-UI default (per §3.1 / §3.2); this spec adds the *toggle* to view a civ's native emergent language, not a *replacement* of English.
- Any change to the existing `EmergenceDashboard` 5-tile struct. The new `language: LanguageDashboard` field is additive; the existing 5 tiles (`cluster_entropy`, `ideology_homophily`, `sentience_fraction`, `psyche_stability`, `diplomacy_tension`) keep their existing contracts and existing tests.
- Any change to the `civ-culture-emergent.md` culture-language macro read-out. That spec's `DialectLabel`, `ScriptSignature`, `ValueSystemBundle`, `RitualPattern`, `TraditionLabel` are unchanged; this spec *extends* the meaning of `ScriptSignature` to include the substrate-conditional projection (per L3-C), but the *function signatures* in `civ-culture-emergent.md` §1.2 are preserved.
- Any change to the `crates/legends/src/worker.rs` `RawSimEvent` wire format. The new event kinds (`linguistic_collapse.v1`, `compositionality_lost.v1`, `script_materialized.v1`) are additive variants; the existing event kinds are unchanged.

---

## 9. References

* Kirby, S. (1999). *Language evolution and the Baldwin effect*. In H. C. Plotkin (Ed.), *The Evolution of Mind* (pp. 207-226). MIT Press. [The iterated-learning + Baldwin effect foundation; the bottleneck-induced compositionality result.]
* Kirby, S. (2001). *Spontaneous evolution of linguistic structure: an iterated learning model of the emergence of regularity and irregularity*. *IEEE Transactions on Evolutionary Computation* 5(2), 102-110. [The Markov-chain attractor model of iterated learning.]
* Brighton, H. & Kirby, S. (2006). *Understanding linguistic evolution by visualizing the emergence of compositional structure*. In *Proceedings of the 28th Annual Conference of the Cognitive Science Society*, 427-432. [The compositionality-index measurement used in §1.4.]
* Brighton, H. (2002). *Compositionality from the Bottleneck: an Iterated Learning Model*. PhD thesis, University of Edinburgh. [The `bottleneck_fraction = 0.4` canonical value used in §1.3 / §4.]
* Smith, K. & Kirby, S. (2008). *Cultural evolution of language*. In *The Evolution of Language: Biolinguistic Approaches*, Cambridge University Press. [The grammar-as-distribution model used in §1.5.]
* Pagel, M., Atkinson, Q. D. & Meade, A. (2007). *Frequency of word-use predicts rates of lexical evolution throughout Indo-European history*. *Nature* 449, 717-720. [The closed-class share band `[0.1, 0.3]` used in §1.5 / §2.4.]
* Everett, D. L. (2013). *Language: The Cultural Tool*. Pantheon Books. [The T/M substrate coupling in §2.1; the language–music coupling in §5.8.]
* Reali, F. & Christiansen, M. H. (2009). *Semantic composition, not categorical correlation, drives the lexical category effect in adults and children*. *Language and Cognitive Processes* 24(10), 1383-1414. [The frequency-based open/closed class distinction in §1.5.]
* Wallace, R. (2002). *Counting the words: A computational approach to the evolution of language*. *Evolution and Cognition* 8(1), 23-32. [The generation-length parameter range cited in §1.2.]
* Bedau, M. A. & Packard, N. H. (1992). *Measurement of emergence*. In *Artificial Life II*, SFI Studies in the Sciences of Complexity X, 435-455. [The supervenience-metric approach used in the dashboard §2.4.]
* Civis codebase: `crates/engine/src/language.rs`, `crates/agents/src/culture.rs`, `crates/agents/src/psyche.rs`, `crates/agents/src/social.rs`, `crates/agents/src/cluster.rs`, `crates/planet/src/geology.rs`, `crates/climate/src/lib.rs`, `crates/voxel/src/{material,fluid_ca,reactions}.rs`, `crates/civ-emergence-metrics/src/dashboard.rs`, `crates/legends/src/{worker,rumor}.rs`, `crates/audio/src/lib.rs`, `crates/watch/`, `crates/server/`.
* Civis design canon: [`docs/guides/emergence-charter.md`](../guides/emergence-charter.md), [`docs/design/emergent-systems-spec.md`](emergent-systems-spec.md), [`docs/design/civ-culture-emergent.md`](civ-culture-emergent.md), [`docs/design/psyche-social.md`](psyche-social.md), [`docs/design/PHYSICS_COUPLING_SUBSTRATE.md`](PHYSICS_COUPLING_SUBSTRATE.md), [`docs/design/emergence-dashboard.md`](emergence-dashboard.md),
